<caption>"Opportunity Cost, Price, &amp; What Stuff is 'Worth'" reproduced with permission from instructor Professor Michael Munger and producer Shaun King</caption></figure></para><para id="eip-452"><title>Watch on YouTube</title><link url="https://youtu.be/95FtkIyvFvA" window="new">https://youtu.be/95FtkIyvFvA</link></para></section><section id="eip-515"><title>Lecture Overview</title><para id="eip-453">
<list id="lectureoverview" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><item>Division of labor is the central concept in all of understanding social institutions. States and markets focus division of labor in different ways, and both are necessary.</item>
  <item>Both markets and states fail when they encourage rent-seeking.</item>
  <item>Opportunity cost: The cost of doing something is the cost of NOT doing other things. Example:
the concert tickets</item>
  <item>Price: When markets work well (and they don't always) price approximates opportunity cost. That 
is important because it gives people all over the world accurate signals about how OTHER people value resources.</item>
  <item>Video: Al Trewis and Moe Cashferme decide whether to grow corn or soy.</item>
  <item>Sock City: Datang, China makes most of the socks in the world, because of division of labor and the price system. Very efficient, but harmful to the workers who used to make socks, but now lost their jobs.</item>
  <item>The whole world is constantly "losing" jobs to productivity increases. Great benefit to consumers.</item>
  <item>An extended example: Recycling. Recycling is expensive. Price system alone would say recycling is a bad idea. But prices here do NOT approximate opportunity cost. May be room for effective state action.</item>
